{{BLP sources|date=June 2018}} {{primary sources|date=June 2018}} '''Harold G. Koenig''' is a [[psychiatrist]] on the faculty of [[Duke University]]. His ideas have been covered in ''[[Newsweek]]'' and other news media with regard to [[Religion and health|religion, spirituality and health]], a focus of some of his research and clinical practice. [[John Templeton Foundation|Templeton Foundation]] has provided great financial support to his activities.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/blindfaithunholy00sloa|title=Blind faith : the unholy alliance of religion and medicine|last=Sloan|first=Richard P.|date=2006|publisher=New York : St. Martin's Press|others=Internet Archive|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=60-63|registration=y}}</ref>
==Education and academic career== Koenig graduated with a B.S. in [[history]] from [[Stanford University]] (1974), later receiving his MD (1982) from [[University of California, San Francisco]].<ref name="cvkoenig">[http://spiritualityandhealth.duke.edu/images/pdfs/Koenig_Full_CV.pdf Curriculum Vitae: Harold G. Koenig], accessed 1 February 2010.</ref> He became Clinical Assistant Professor in Psychiatry (1992) and has been Professor of Psychiatry (2004-) at [[Duke University]] Medical Center.
He is currently director of Duke's Center for the Study of Religion/Spirituality and Health.
==Research== Koenig has published over 280 scientific articles in peer-reviewed journals, scholarly professional journal articles and 60 chapters in professional books.<ref name=cvkoenig/> In a cooperation with [[Raphael M. Bonelli]] from [[Sigmund Freud University Vienna]] he undertook the first systematic [[evidence based]] analysis on the connection between [[mental disorder]]s and [[religion]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Bonelli | first1 = RM | last2 = Koenig | first2 = H | year = 2013 | title = Mental Disorders, Religion and Spirituality 1990 to 2010: A Systematic Evidence-Based Review | url = | journal = Journal of Religion and Health | volume = 52| issue = 2| pages = 657–73| pmid = 23420279 | doi=10.1007/s10943-013-9691-4}}</ref> The researchers conclude that there is good [[evidence]] that religious involvement is correlated with better mental health in the areas of [[Depression (mood)|depression]], [[substance abuse]], and [[suicide]]; some evidence in [[Stress-related disorders]] and [[dementia]]; insufficient evidence in [[bipolar disorder]] and [[schizophrenia]], and no data in many other mental disorders.
==Media coverage== Koenig's ideas have been covered in a wide variety of news media, ranging from BBC radio to the Vatican Radio.<ref name=cvkoenig/> Examples include:
* In 2009, ''Newsweek'' featured comments from Koenig, stating that he was "leading the charge for a better understanding of patients' religious and spiritual beliefs in the medical setting. 'It just makes too much sense,' he says, when patient after patient tells him, 'Doctor, religion is the most important thing; it keeps me going.' Koenig advocates that doctors take spiritual histories of any patient they are likely to have an ongoing relationship with, asking questions like: 'Is religion a source of comfort or stress? Do you have any religious beliefs that would influence decision-making? Do you have any spiritual needs that someone should address?'"<ref>Claudia Kalb (2003, Nov. 10). "[http://www.newsweek.com/faith-healing-133365 Can Religion Improve Health? While The Debate Rages In Journals And Med Schools, More Americans Ask For Doctors' Prayers ]." ''[[Newsweek]]''.</ref>
