[[File:SaulMerin1.jpg|thumbnail|Saul Merin (Jerusalem, 2004)]]
'''Saul Cvi Merin''' ({{lang-he|שאול מרין}}; August 25, 1933 – August 28, 2012) was an Israeli [[ophthalmologist]] specializing in the diagnosis and treatment of [[Retinal diseases|retinal]] and  [[Genetic disease|genetic]] [[eye diseases]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stjohneyehospital.org/saul-merin-friend-hospital-group-passes-away-jerusalem |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130102111215/http://www.stjohneyehospital.org/saul-merin-friend-hospital-group-passes-away-jerusalem|archivedate=2 January 2013|title=Saul Merin, Friend to the Hospital Group, Passes Away in Jerusalem |publisher=St John Eye Hospital |date=1943-08-03 |accessdate=2012-11-22}}</ref>  His book ''Inherited Eye Diseases'' is now in its second edition.

As Professor of Ophthalmology at Israel's [[Hadassah Hospital]], Merin worked at the [[St John Eye Hospital Group]]'s East Jerusalem hospital, where he worked with ophthalmologists working in the area of the [[Palestinian National Authority]].

While based primarily in Israel, worked for 25 years with [[The University of Illinois Eye and Ear Infirmary]], where was a [[visiting professor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uic.edu/com/eye/Department/Publications/Annual%20Reports/AR2004/AR04%20alumni.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120218212919/http://www.uic.edu/com/eye/Department/Publications/Annual%20Reports/AR2004/AR04%20alumni.pdf|archivedate=18 February 2012|work=Alumni & Friends|title=Saul D. Merin, MD|publisher=[[University of Illinois at Chicago]]}}</ref>

== Early life==
Merin escaped [[deportation]] by train to [[Auschwitz]] on August 3, 1943, and was hidden by Aniela (Zawadzka) Szwajce in [[Będzin]],<ref>[http://db.yadvashem.org/righteous/family.html?language=en&itemId=4832513 About Zawadzka] at the Righteous Among the Nations Database, [[Yad Vashem]] website</ref> a town in southwest [[Poland]], until arrival of the Soviet army in January 1945.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.yadvashem.org/about_yad/magazine/magazine_new/mag_36/Prayer.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20080906090725/http://www1.yadvashem.org/about_yad/magazine/magazine_new/mag_36/Prayer.html|dead-url=yes|archive-date=2008-09-06|title=No Prayer, No Breakfast|author=Mordechai Paldiel|work=Yad Vashem magazine|date=2004}}</ref> He emigrated to Israel in 1949.

==Career==
He studied at the Medical School of [[Hebrew University]] in Jerusalem from 1953-1960. Following conscription into Army Service in the [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]] from 1961-1963, he
trained in ophthalmology at [[Hadassah Medical Center]] under Professor I.C. Michaelson from 1963-1969, and was made a specialist in ophthalmology in 1969.

He worked in [[Malawi]] from 1965-1967, and made several professional tours in Africa.

He was awarded fellowships{{which|date=December 2014}} and had additional training at the [[Hospital for Sick Children]], [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada in [[pediatric ophthalmology]], and at the [[University of Illinois at Chicago]], [[Illinois]], USA for further medical study of the [[retina]].

He was Professor of Ophthalmology at Hebrew University from 1979 until his death. He was Chairman of the [[Israel Ophthalmological Society]] from 1976-1982, Chairman of the [[Israel Society for Vision and Eye Research]] from 1985-1995, Chairman of the [[Israel Board of Ophthalmology]], from 1989-1995, and Chairman of the Unit of Ophthalmology, at Hadassah Hospital on [[Mount Scopus]] from 1979-1998.

Prof. Merin died in August 2012.

